Part 6

The telephone call came eleven days later. Vikram was back at the head office in Calcutta, in the middle of a tedious meeting about new tea packaging labels. 

The directors were arguing over the size of the company logo on the cardboard boxes. Vikram stepped out into the quiet corridor to take the call on his mobile.

"You won't believe this," Reddy's voice said from the receiver. For once in his life, the senior director sounded like he meant the phrase literally, rather than using it as a figure of speech.

"What happened, Reddy?"

"The local MLA called Minister Satyanarayana's office yesterday afternoon," Reddy said. "He told them to process our land allocation file immediately. No conditions, no delays, no extra meetings."

"Why?" Vikram asked, looking through the corridor glass.

"Nobody knows why. That is the part I don't believe," Reddy exhaled audibly down the line. "The man has been sitting on this file for two years, blocking it for reasons nobody could ever get straight. And now, suddenly, it's done."

Vikram listened to the hum of the phone line.

"Doesn't matter," Reddy continued. "Take the win, Vikram. And it gets even better. They have allotted double the acreage we originally asked for. Somebody upstairs must have decided to make it worth our while, or make up for lost time, or God knows what. I stopped trying to explain government logic years ago."

Vikram looked out through the glass wall of the office corridor. Below, the ordinary Tuesday traffic of Calcutta crawled along the main street, people going about their ordinary errands with no idea that a two-year corporate deadlock somewhere else had just, inexplicably, come undone.

"Vikram? You there?" Reddy asked. "This is very good news, in case that wasn't clear."

"I heard you, Reddy. It is good news."

"You don't sound like it is good news."

"I am glad," Vikram said. He checked himself honestly, and found that he was—it was a clean, quiet gladness, without the fist-clenched triumph he might once have felt at the same news a year ago. "I just don't feel like I need to do anything loud about being glad. Does that make sense?"

"No," Reddy said. "But congratulations anyway. I will meet you at the site next week."

---

That evening, alone in the hotel room he still hadn't gotten used to, Vikram found the folded paper again. It was in the inside pocket of his jacket, where he had been carrying it without quite noticing he had.

He sat on the floor, crossing his legs the way the shaky sketch showed. He closed his eyes and breathed, doing it for the ten minutes the paper said, no more.

He did not feel suddenly transformed. He didn't feel anything cinematic or magical. 

He felt, mostly, like a man who had stopped needing the outcome to arrive on time in order to keep doing his work anyway. He suspected, without being able to say exactly why, that this was the entire point of the exercise, and probably the entire point of the word he had been given. 

Somewhere past the hotel window, past the city traffic, past several states, a small fire was probably still burning at the edge of a coffee plantation. It was tended by a man who would likely never know what his ash and his silence had helped set in motion.

Vikram didn't call the plantation to tell anyone. Some things, he was beginning to understand, were not owed an explanation. Not even a grateful one.

He went back to his desk and his files that night, feeling lighter than he had in years. The land allocation, when it finally arrived on official government stamp paper three weeks later, felt less like a hard-fought victory than like a simple fact he had already made peace with in advance.

